# Fast-model candidates for the conversational loop

## Recommendation

Trial these in order:

1. **`anthropic/claude-haiku-4.5`** — best first bet. It keeps the Anthropic family, so persona and tool behavior have the smallest migration risk, while OpenRouter's current best-provider p50 TTFT is **0.41s**, less than half Sonnet 4.6's **0.86s** live OpenRouter p50 and roughly one-third of our **1.28s real-call median**.
2. **`openai/gpt-5.4-mini` with reasoning minimized/disabled** — best cross-family quality challenger. Current OpenRouter best-provider p50 is **0.82s** with low observed tool-call error rates. It is cheaper than Haiku on input and similarly priced on output.
3. **`openai/gpt-4.1-mini`** — mature cheap control. Current OpenRouter best-provider p50 is **0.75s** and provider tool-call errors are 0–1.08%. A voice practitioner calls GPT-4.1 the safe tool-heavy default; Mini preserves the API/tool shape at much lower cost, but its quality must be proven on our 15-tool prompt.

Do **not** put Gemini 3.1 Flash Lite in the first three. It is fast and cheap, but OpenRouter's current provider data shows **5.51–8.18% tool-call error**, too risky for a tool-heavy live call. Keep it as the speed-floor follow-up if Exacto routing or our own test disproves that concern.

## Comparison

OpenRouter values below are live one-week figures observed 2026-07-13. They move with provider load. “TTFT” is OpenRouter's `Latency` metric: time to first token.

| Model | OpenRouter p50 TTFT, best provider | Observed tool-call error | Price / 1M input → output | Normalized call cost* | Read |
|---|---:|---:|---:|---:|---|
| Baseline: `anthropic/claude-sonnet-4.6` | 0.86s; our calls 1.28s median / 5.4s p95 | 0.10–0.68% among best shown providers | $3 → $15 | **$0.1275** | Quality ceiling; tail latency is the problem |
| **`anthropic/claude-haiku-4.5`** | **0.41s** | 0.18–1.85% | $1 → $5 | **$0.0425** | Same-family swap; strongest first experiment |
| **`openai/gpt-5.4-mini`** | **0.82s** | 0.26–0.75% | $0.75 → $4.50 | **$0.0323** | Strong tool/agent positioning; disable reasoning |
| **`openai/gpt-4.1-mini`** | **0.75s** | 0–1.08% | $0.40 → $1.60 | **$0.0168** | Cheap, mature, concise control |
| Hold: `google/gemini-3.1-flash-lite` | **0.66s** | **5.51–8.18%** | $0.25 → $1.50 | **$0.0108** | Fastest cheap option, but current tool reliability is a red flag |

\*Normalized cost is not a measured call bill. It prices a fixed ten-turn call with 4,000 input tokens resent per turn and 50 output tokens per turn: 40,000 input + 500 output tokens. Actual cost depends heavily on prompt caching, transcript growth, and tool round trips.

## Why Haiku first

- [Anthropic's latency guide](https://platform.claude.com/docs/en/test-and-evaluate/strengthen-guardrails/reduce-latency) names Haiku 4.5 as its speed-critical model.
- [OpenRouter's Haiku 4.5 page](https://openrouter.ai/anthropic/claude-haiku-4.5) currently shows 0.41s best-provider p50 TTFT, 89 tok/s, and 0.18–1.85% tool-call errors across the fastest reported providers.
- A [2026 voice-agent comparison](https://wildrunai.com/blog/llm-comparison-voice-agents-2026) reports sub-600ms median TTFT and says Haiku inherits Anthropic's strong instruction following on speech-recognition transcripts. It warns that deeply nested multi-tool flows are less consistent than Sonnet. Our 15-tool surface makes that the main acceptance gate.
- A separate [streaming latency test](https://www.kunalganglani.com/blog/llm-api-latency-benchmarks-2026) measured Haiku at 597ms and found it more concise than Gemini Flash. Concision matters because the persona must speak in short turns.

## Why GPT-5.4 Mini second

- [OpenRouter](https://openrouter.ai/openai/gpt-5.4-mini) positions it for chat and agent workflows. Current data shows 0.82s best-provider p50, 68 tok/s, and tool-call errors of 0.26% on Azure and 0.75% on OpenAI.
- [Softcery's 2026 voice guide](https://softcery.com/lab/ai-voice-agents-choosing-the-right-llm) recommends non-reasoning/minimal reasoning for voice and reports medium effort can push Mini TTFT to roughly 8.24s. The A/B configuration must pin the lowest available reasoning mode rather than inherit a coding-agent default.
- OpenRouter's page reports a 73.3% IFBench instruction-following score and 83.3% on the telecom slice of τ²-Bench. Those are supporting signals, not substitutes for our persona and tool tests.

## Why GPT-4.1 Mini third

- [OpenRouter](https://openrouter.ai/openai/gpt-4.1-mini) reports 0.75s best-provider p50, $0.40/$1.60 pricing, an 84.1% IFEval score, and tool support through the standard OpenRouter API.
- Current provider data shows low tool-call error, including 0% on the small Azure EU sample, 0.14% on Azure, and 1.08% on OpenAI.
- Practitioner evidence conflicts on latency. [WildRun AI](https://wildrunai.com/blog/llm-comparison-voice-agents-2026) reports the full GPT-4.1 around 450ms and calls it the safest production default for tool-heavy voice. A [small independent streaming test](https://www.kunalganglani.com/blog/llm-api-latency-benchmarks-2026) measured GPT-4.1 Mini near 2.4s. That disagreement is exactly why this candidate belongs in a real-call A/B rather than being selected from a chart.

## Joel's added cells

Joel added three LOW-reasoning cells after the first ranking. All three exact slugs exist in OpenRouter's live model catalog, advertise tool support, and accept `reasoning.effort: "low"`:

| Trial cell | OpenRouter p50 TTFT, best provider | Observed tool-call error | Price / 1M input → output | Normalized call cost* | Read |
|---|---:|---:|---:|---:|---|
| **`x-ai/grok-4.5`**, LOW | **0.91s** | 0.66–0.82% | $2 → $6 | **$0.0830** | Credible tool cell, but not faster on the current headline than the first three |
| **`openai/gpt-5.6-luna`**, LOW | **1.64s** | 0.11–2.76% | $1 → $6 | **$0.0430** | Cheap 5.6 cell; current aggregate TTFT is slower than our real-call baseline median |
| **`openai/gpt-5.6-terra`**, LOW | **1.53s** | 0.78–4.34% on providers with reported latency | $2.50 → $15 | **$0.1075** | Higher-capability cell, not a published-speed winner |

Receipts observed 2026-07-13:

- [Grok 4.5 on OpenRouter](https://openrouter.ai/x-ai/grok-4.5): exact slug `x-ai/grok-4.5`; 0.91s best-provider p50; xAI provider tool-call error 0.82% and xAI ZDR 0.66%; $2/$6 per million tokens.
- [GPT-5.6 Luna on OpenRouter](https://openrouter.ai/openai/gpt-5.6-luna): exact slug `openai/gpt-5.6-luna`; 1.64s best-provider p50; tool-call error 0.11% on Azure EU, 0.54% on Azure, and 2.76% on OpenAI; $1/$6 per million tokens.
- [GPT-5.6 Terra on OpenRouter](https://openrouter.ai/openai/gpt-5.6-terra): exact slug `openai/gpt-5.6-terra`; 1.53s best-provider p50; tool-call error 0.78% on Azure and 4.34% on OpenAI; $2.50/$15 per million tokens. OpenRouter also displays 0% for Azure EU, but that endpoint currently has no reported latency or throughput, so it is excluded from the comparison range.
- OpenRouter's [reasoning configuration](https://openrouter.ai/docs/guides/best-practices/reasoning-tokens) uses `{"reasoning":{"effort":"low"}}`. The live catalog reports LOW support for all three. Grok requires reasoning and defaults to HIGH; Luna and Terra default to MEDIUM, so the trial must set LOW explicitly.

**Updated ranking:** the published data does **not** displace the original top three. Keep Haiku 4.5 first, GPT-5.4 Mini second, and GPT-4.1 Mini third. Put Grok 4.5 next as the strongest added cell. Luna and Terra remain useful Joel-requested behavior/quality probes, but their current aggregate OpenRouter p50 TTFT is above the existing shortlist and above our 1.28s real-call median. OpenRouter does not break its public latency chart down by reasoning effort, so LOW may perform better than these mixed-traffic figures; the real-call A/B decides it.

\*Same normalized ten-turn call used above: 40,000 input + 500 output tokens. Reasoning tokens are billed as output, so LOW trials may cost more than this text-only estimate.

## Trial gates

Use the same recorded call set and tool schemas for every model. A model advances only if it:

1. Cuts real-call median TTFT by at least 30% without worsening p95.
2. Produces no malformed tool arguments and no material increase in wrong-tool or missed-tool calls.
3. Keeps replies terse, preserves the Aussie persona, and does not narrate tool machinery.
4. Preserves interruption recovery and does not turn tool latency into unexplained dead air.

Route by exact model and provider policy during the experiment. OpenRouter offers **Nitro** for speed and **Exacto** for tool-call accuracy; changing routing mode mid-cell would muddle the result. [OpenRouter documents those modes on each model page](https://openrouter.ai/openai/gpt-5.4-mini).
